Chapter 1
Coren
4:30, Itania time. Cohren hated waking up so early. Especially since it was his responsibility to wake up all the other members of his company. He quietly got out of his bunk, put on his combat uniform, put on his tactical vest and gathered the items from his locker, paying particular attention to a small box. He slung his rifle over his shoulder and hung his helmet on a small hook attached to his belt. The helmet was fully equipped: respirator, goggles, everything. After checking his ammo pouches, he quietly left the barracks, the sound of mud and crushed ice echoing under his boots.
He pulled out a lighter from the pocket of his jacket and a cigarette from the other. On lighting it, he took a small puff before gently opening the door. The previous week, he had had to be creative to wake up the men and women under his command. He had stopped using the preset alarm, half the time it didn't work, as everything coming out of the speakers was a faint hiss.
"Are you waking them up?" Cohren turned to see Second Lieutenant Nemic walking in.
"Ugh", replied Cohren.
"What do you plan to use this time?"
Before he could answer, the door opened and Harris, Craith, and other soldiers rushed out, already dressed and equipped.
"Hello", said Craith.
"What woke you up?", Cohren asked.
"Well, primo, we didn't want to see what you had planned to wake us up today. Secundo, the first shock troops up are the first to breakfast." One of them, Ravik, replied: "And you know how bad it can be."
"You score a point, Specialist," said Cohren. He extended his hand and flipped a switch. An alarm sounded loudly inside the barrack, loud and screaming. He heard a commotion inside and chaos.
"Good blood, Valturi", Nemic said. "We should have thought they'd have learned to rise at the same time as you by now."
"Well, my buddies from the training camp here did it", Cohren turned to Harris, Craith and Ravik. "But, again, their group and platoon leaders know how to get up before their units."
A few seconds later, the rest of the company came out in a mass. Everyone had what they needed, from personal belongings to necessary equipment. Some of the new recruits looked disoriented, others more annoyed.
"Hello everyone," said Cohren in a cheerful voice.
"Except for your respect, chief, why do you insist on waking us up in this manner?", asked one of the shock troop members, a corporal.
Because standard alarms are terrible. And because Daybreak doesn't do morning snoozes," Cohren retorted.
"See to it that you have all your personal belongings", he continued. As a first lieutenant and the commander's assistant, it was his responsibility to oversee and assist the company with the company commander, Captain Boradin Shaw. "We won't be coming back. Sergeants and second lieutenants, I give you and your units fifty minutes to conduct the final checks and retrieve the day's rations."
The members of the Exodus company dispersed. They were part of the second shock troops division, second army. Initially, they were separated into two distinct companies, Cohort and Dragger, before being reunited. It was a scattered company and Cohren did not know what to make of his promotion to first lieutenant, mainly the reasons that had motivated him.
Cohren and Nemic, the leader of the first platoon, marched together under the light of the base's many operational illuminations, powered by generators. Most were painted red to camouflage them from enemy bombers. Daybreak had resorted to Wild Weasel assaults, both in the air and on the ground, to counter them.
"New day, new mission for the pioneers of hell", began Nemesis with a dry laugh. "Where are they sending us?"
"A forward operational base outside of Ianlos. We were sent to support the ground assault," Cohren replied, taking a drag on his cigarette. A part of him blamed Craith for introducing him to smoking, but a year of combat changes a man, and he fell silent."
"Merde. The situation is deteriorating on the front", Nemic muttered. "All the news coming from that place is 'Contribute to the war effort. Send aid to the Kurgan front'. Why can't we send aid to the Howland front?"
"Amen, my brother," Cohren said, flicking his cigarette butt into the mud. "Anyway, we're heading out with the first armored platoon, so we won't have to march. Captain Shaw should be there."
"Did Shaw have a ride?", Nemic asked, a bit surprised.
"Yes, I mean, honestly, he's not as bad as I thought he'd be. I mean, he's not exceptional, but he's not unbearable."
Coren raised his thumb and index finger to his throat mic while adjusting his backpack. "To all units of Company Exodus, proceed to the western vehicle park when you're done. We're departing with the first armored platoon at 0500."
Every few seconds, he received responses from squadron leaders. Haris, Craith, and Ravik were all low-ranking non-commissioned officers when they got here. All four had been very close friends since their initial training on Earth. It seemed to go back so far, even though it couldn't be more than two years. They were then squadron leaders. But Craith was now commanding the second platoon for a week, after the demobilization of the previous commander, who was injured by a Daybreak sniper.
As they walked toward the vehicle park, Cohren and Nemic saw a group of about eight main battle tanks, Kronos, and four Strykers. Their crew was busy, making sure their war machines were ready for departure. Cohren quickly spotted Captain Boradin Shaw, who was talking to the tank platoon commander. As they approached, Shaw turned and walked toward them, his normally cold face reflecting no emotion.
Lieutenant Nemic... Lieutenant Valturi..." He said Cohren was slower, looking at Cohren's pistol holster before looking at them again. "I suppose the company is ready."
